Without the tenure system, the univer-
sity of the 21st century cannot house a
free exchange of ideas, said an associate
professor of philosophy at Pitt, Tamara

I Horowitz.

“We couldn’t have the university as
we know it without tenure,” she said at a
workshop. “We couldn’t have people
speaking out on controversial issues.”

Horowitz spoke at a workshop
Thursday that addressed the question of
whether tenure will survive in the 21st
century.

Horowitz addressed a 1978 article
entitled “Tenure: A Conscientious
Objection,” in which the author, James
O’Toole, argues for the abolition of
tenure.

According to Horowitz, O’Toole
wrote that abolishing tenure would
allow more young people to enter acade-
mia positions and would give faculty
members the ﬂexibility to explore other
career options. Some argue that faculty
members remain in university positions
only because tenure offers them securi-

ty, she said. .

The article states that abolishing
tenure will not suppress intellectual
freedom. If a university fires a faculty
member for his/her radical views, the
professor could just go to another uni-
versity with the same radical views.

But Horowitz cited a case in the 1960s
when a radical math professor was fired.
He couldn’t get a job anywhere else in
the United States and had to leave the
country.

“So the argument that other universi-
ties will snap up the radical professor is
false,” she said. '

Tenure was designed to encourage
intellectual freedom, said Pitt Faculty of
Arts and Sciences Dean Peter Koehler in
a telephone interview. It allows a faculty
member to speak out on controversial
issues, because it extends to the faculty
member a permanent contract, he said.

Others at the workshop pointed out the
faults of the tenure system.

“I think tenure will survive, but how
do we fix it?” said the associate dean of
Carnegie Mellon University. “What do
you do about people who are no longer
productive members of the communi-

 

