Build shuttle shelters

The University of Pittsburgh transportation has improved in
the last couple of years, but there are still improvements to be
made. One suggestion of The Pitt News is to create shuttle shel-
ters. Many of the City of Pittsburgh bus stops have rain and
wind shelters. If PAT can protect us from the elements, then
why can’t Pitt? Students are often sitting outside the William
Pitt Union waiting for their shuttle. This is fine if it is a nice,
sunny, late-summer day. But when the rain is coming down or
the wind blowing, it would be nice to have some protection
from the elements. It would make it easier for students to identi-
fy where shuttle stops are. Building these shelters‘ would likely
be very easy to do and inexpensive (assuming the red tape can
be avoided), and would be a much greater improvement than a
campus clock.

Another needed improvement is more schedule information.
One can always get schedules in the union, but it would be con-
venient if they were available elsewhere. A permanent structure
in front of the union, next to the campus map would be a
desired improvement. Ideally, this structure would list all routes
and times as a convenient reference point for students.
Furthermore, route maps posted on the new shuttle shelters,
showing where and when the shuttles that stop there go, would
be very convenient for students. Also on general principle,
making route schedules more available on campus would be
greatly desirable.

These simple and inexpensive improvements would go a long
way toward making the university shuttle system more user-
friendly and would make getting around campus that much eas-

lgpeed limit should be 65

You are driving down the Ohio Turnpike, entering
Pennsylvania. The first thing you see is the “Welcome to
Pennsylvania, the Speed Limit is Still 55” sign. Then you are
“politely” informed of the triple-digit cost of speeding tickets.
Enough is enough. It is time for Pennsylvania to finally take a
step back from social repression and raise the speed limit to 65
miles per hour. V

Many states have entered the ‘90s and have raised their speed
limit to 65. There is no real reason for the speed limit to stay at
55. A 10-mile-an-hour increase would cut by almost 20 percent
the time required to travel from point A to point B.
Furthermore, studies have shown there is not a significant
increase in auto accidents when highway speed limits are high-
er. Most accidents occur at dangerous intersections rather than
on highways.

Ultimately, there is not a good enough reason for our state to
have a speed limitat 55. The de facto speed limit is basically
already 65. It is time for Pennsylvania to loosen up a little. For
our overly paternalistic state to limit our speed limit, thereby
slowing our lives down, is just plain wrong.

