The role of ROTC on Pii'i's campus

wo weeks ago, while
some of us were sit-
ting discussing the

Renaissance, we heard martial
strains floating into the class
from the Cathedral lawn.
Being naturally curious, as stu-
dents ought to be, we ventured
down after class to find out
what was happening.

When we stepped out of the
door, we saw maybe30 ROTC
cadets in formations. There
were some officers milling
around in front of the forma-
tion. They were being
addressed by one of their supe-
riors, and they looked ready to
march off to Haiti or Bosnia or
some other world hot spot.

A friend, who is admittedly a
little to the left of Karl Marx,
said to me that she didn’t think
the university ought to be
training better killers. This was
a slightly‘ unnerving thought.
The military’s job, however, at
its basest level, is killing the
enemy (whomever our national
leaders in their infinite wisdom
decide that is). “Defending the
Constitution” sounds better,
but it is a euphemism. The uni-
versity (as an idea now) is
designed to promote under-
standing and attainment. The
military may promote attain-
ment, but its promotion of
understanding is something
akin to that of a Mafia Cappo.
They promote an understand-
ing of the American point of
view by blowing a few things
up, shooting some folks and,
sometimes, they even succeed.

Upon further reflection, it
seemed that if the ROTC was a
necessary evil, then the univer-
sity wasn’t living up to the sec-
ond part of the idea.
Specifically, it didn’t seem to
be promoting the attainment of
a higher form of killing.

For instance, why don’t Pitt
students hear the constant
cracking of riﬂes, the shouts of
close-order drills and see hand-
to-hand combat practice on the
Cathedral lawn? If Pitt is going

to be involved in the training
of better killers, then they
ought to do it expeditiously.
Set up bayonet dummies in
front of the William Pitt Union
and hold rappelling drills
down the Cathedral. With all
the helicopters bringing in
spare people parts for the hos-
pital or serious emergency
cases, who would notice the
added noise of air assault prac-

’ tice on various sites on cam-

pus? A practice assault on
Sutherland Hall would liven
up the old study breaks and
test the security Pitt has hired
to guard its dorms.

Well, it turns out that the
ROTC’s program is not
designed to turn out soldiers,
sailors and airmen per se. I
spoke with members of the
military (a sin for which my
dear friend the hippie—chick
will never forgive me) and
observed some of the groups
of cadets on campus. It seems
that, ideally, the ROTC pro-
gram is designed to train lead-
ers, not killers.

The cadets are supposed to
be students first. The concept
is that they develop discipline
through their education and
some ancillary exercises pro-
vided courtesy of the
Department of Defense.

Their first required military
training does not occur until
the summer between their
junior and senior years. They
are supposed to learn some-
thing besides how to plan ans
invasion. Sometimes, they
learn something the military
can apply directly, like engi-
neering. At other times, they
have something less directly
applicable to the function of
the army. There are few fine
arts majors, for example, but at
the same time, there are no
requirements that a cadet have
a specific major.

The first question that comes
to mind is: “Why aren’t the
military academies taking
charge of training the new offi-

cers?” It turns out that they
don’t produce enough officers
to fill the demand. Every year
more officers leave, one way
or another, than the service
academies grind out to fill
their place.

Actually, putting the future
military leaders in the universi-
ty setting makes more sense
than keeping them sequestered
in training camps. First, an
educa'ted"force'is' needed to be
more efficient, less costly and
less of a danger to itself. All of
those video game weapons
need someone competent to
use them, and you can’t draft
an army from video arcades.

Second, it helps the preven-
tion of the development of -a
warrior class. The last thing
this country needs is a group of
people who see themselves as
some sort of samurai class. It
keeps them in touch with their
civilian side, “that civilian

within all of us” to borrow -

support group jargon.

Finally, the cadets have to be
in an environment with
peaceniks, Lenny Bruce fans
and even socialists (yes, there
are some still left) so they are
exposed to more free thinking
than they would ever find in a
boot camp. Thus, they are
more likely to think things
over before sliding into a doc-
trinaire stance.

While the United States may
want an army that is possessed
of straight shooters, they can’t
all be grunts. The fact that they
aren’t is what prevents the
nonsense seen in other coun-
tries. There is no daily coup
d’etat in Washington. So,
while the military may make
some of us nervous, it’s better
to have them up close. This
way, we can keep a better eye
on them and even influence
them a little. If we don’t, then
it won’t be long before Big
Brother will be keeping his eye
on us.

Benjamin Jackson is a colum-
nist for The Pitt News.

