Rugby
continues

a streak

By Michael Kovak
For The Pitt News

The Pitt rugby A team raised
its season record to 4-0 with a
26-18 victory over rival West
Virginia Saturday at
Morgantown.

Team captain Brian Vahosky
got Pitt rolling early in the first
half with a 35-meter run set up
by a J.D. Groff pass. A Sean
Tonkin conversion gave Pitt a
7-0 lead, which would not be
relinquished.

WVU quickly responded,
however, with a score, but the
conversion failed, narrowing
Pitt’s advantage to 7-5.

Tom Marsden, with a lot of
help from his teammates, bull-
dozed his way into the tri—zone
for the next Panther score. The
successful conversion put Pitt
ahead 14-5.

Momentum continued to
stay in— Pitt’s favor. Matt
Fleisman, playing in his first A
squad game, scored on an exit-
ing 45-meter run, dodging sev-
eral Mountaineer defenders
along the way.

“Hopefully, Matt will be
able to come up with a lot
more plays like that,” Pitt
rugby president Chris Fortin
said. '

After Fleisman’s score, Pitt
had a 21-5 lead, and the first
half came to a close.

As much as Pitt controlled
the first half, the opposite was
true in the second half.

“West Virginia was in our
zone for about 75 percent of
the second half. Our defense
bent, but it didn’t break. We
denied them quite a few times

‘in the second half,“ Fortin

said.

WVU began the second half
with a score to get within nine
at 21-12. The stingy Pitt
defense would only allow a
drop kick and a field goal for
the remainder of the game.

The only score inithe second
half for Pitt came from Brian
McNally, who was filling in
for Mike Barron. Tonkin
missed the conversion.

This is the second consecu-
tive year Pitt has defeated
WVU. The B squad was not as
fortunate though, losing 8-3.

Dave Jaeger, vice-president
of the rugby club, said, “The
forwards played really well.
We kept pushing them back.
The problem was that our
loose play was poor.

“Our backs are still inexperi-
enced, but they showed a lot of
promise. All in all, we could
have played a lot better.”

Pitt’s next opponent is Penn

' State this Saturday in State

College.

“We’re on a roll, and this is
a really big match for us,“
Fortin said of Pitt’s upcoming
match.

