er] Johnny Bell for making key
blocks. It’s a pass play that has
to develop quickly in a timing
pattern, and it turned out per-
fect.”

Just when it seemed as if the
Panthers were going to complete
another successful drive in the
fourth quarter, a holding penalty

forced Pitt to settle on Merrick’s
final field goal, a 40-yarder,
which was also Pitt’s ﬁnal points
of the game. The Panthers led
29-24 with 11:47 left in the
game.

Sensing the victory, Lowe
threw over the outstretched arms
of Panther safety David Sumner
for a 49-yard bomb to freshman
receiver John Bell. J

“The long bomb and theyrun
that was 80'-yards long, I
shouldn’t of been playing peri-
od,” Sumner said. “I messed up.
I couldn’t do anything right. I
would say that I [screwed] up,
but I won’t say it.”

Three plays later, Louisville
took the lead for good as
Shelman scored his ﬁnal touch-
down on a 4-yarder, making it a
30-29 game.

The Panthers had ample
opportunities to regain the lead,
but key mistakes kept them from
obtaining their goal.

With 9:00 left in the game,
Fitzgerald was penalized 23
yards for intentional grounding.
Two plays later, on a third-and-

33 situation, a wide open Billy
Davis dropped a 40-yard
Fitzgerald pass.

“I just got a little greedy,”
Davis said, commenting on the
dropped pass. “When I got
greedy, I just wasn’t concentrat-
ing.”

Then at 6:30 left in the game,
West fumbled the ball on his
own 24-yard line. Louisville’s
Alan Campos recovered the ball
on the Panther 9-yard line, set-
ting up the final points of the
game on 22-yard Akers field
goal.

Pitt got another chance three
minutes later. But like last time,
West lost the ball. This time he
was stripped by Rico Clark, and
the ball was recovered by
Louisville’s Tony Bethel.

“I was the goat on that one,”
West said. “As a young player
you have to put them behind
you. When I wake up tomorrow,
it just got to be over. There is
nothing you can do about this
game. It hurts. You just got to
remember the feeling of losing
hurts.”

